[{"_id":"1223c9e0-4640-11ed-b2ac-73099b4bce4d","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"4ef3ee20-4615-11ed-af67-fbac7ea67732","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"Indeed; thank you!","date":"2022-10-07T13:00:51.674Z"},{"_id":"4ef3ee20-4615-11ed-af67-fbac7ea67732","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","authorName":"Jacob","authorUri":"","message":"It seems like the `record` and `struct` keywords have been switches around in the CustomerId example above.","date":"2022-10-07T07:54:45.284Z"},{"_id":"612c4590-4676-11ed-9eba-37844a6d86a0","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"877ddef0-4673-11ed-9eba-37844a6d86a0","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"Thanks! I have fixed that typo. My blog is heavily cached, so it'll just take a while to propagate everywhere.","date":"2022-10-07T19:29:37.023Z"},{"_id":"877ddef0-4673-11ed-9eba-37844a6d86a0","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"0470d91615bbd75e864b509a4bc5e395","authorName":"Sean Feldman","authorUri":"","message":"That is a good and practical suggestion. Thank you.\r\n\r\nThe code snippet has \"struct record\" rather than \"record struct\". Might want to update that.","date":"2022-10-07T19:09:12.866Z"},{"_id":"9bb8e6d0-4669-11ed-9435-f5c69076f9e8","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"ca70c1c0-4662-11ed-8134-878adb3eb81e","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"Thanks!","date":"2022-10-07T17:58:11.853Z"},{"_id":"ca70c1c0-4662-11ed-8134-878adb3eb81e","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","authorName":"","authorUri":"","message":"Solving Primitive Obsesesion with Value Objects.\r\n\r\nObsession spelt wrong in section title","date":"2022-10-07T17:09:23.772Z"},{"_id":"7d5a50b0-485e-11ed-b8aa-b9c9b5e9b3ca","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","authorName":"Kirill","authorUri":"","message":"Hi! You suggest to avoid dealing with serialization of value objects and I agree with it. But what to do with the case when user of my library wants to transfer over the nework some object which returned by the library and which contains Value Objects? Should they unwrap Value Objects to primitives in their code where they map these models to DTOs?","date":"2022-10-10T05:43:38.751Z"},{"_id":"08e36a80-4d1f-11ed-8e57-ad3baf1781d2","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"5621d2e9e945346b6cd16f3c0b0eec14","authorName":"Jack Kendall","authorUri":"","message":"One issue I've had with using records for this in the past is preventing invalid values. Say I want an `Age` value type which is an `int` with values limited to between 0 and 100.\r\n\r\nI obviously don't want to let myself make one with a value of 101, so I have to either throw an exception in the `Age` constructor (yuck) or create a static `TryCreate` method, which I have to check the success state of every time I make an `Age`. In either case, I'm losing a lot of the simplicity garnered by the one-line record syntax.\r\n\r\nMaybe I shouldn't consider this a core part of value objects, as opposed to just having strong types for business concepts?","date":"2022-10-16T06:52:00.844Z"},{"_id":"74709710-6e9d-11ed-92eb-7ff19b5e5bb3","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"08e36a80-4d1f-11ed-8e57-ad3baf1781d2","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"58a23a045edda5db95d659c95afc3529","authorName":"Jason","authorUri":"","message":"I'm struggling with this right now as well. I don't like the fact that I can use with or the default constructor and have an invalid object. I'm unsure how to handle this other than verifying that its valid at the boundary and then using it within the domain without the need to check if its valid every time. Basically, how do I embrace the mostly valid state versus always valid state.\r\n\r\nOne question I have for your Age type is the range, does your domain care about the 0 to 100 or is it a 'technical' limit. Can this validation be outside the domain (via model binding, etc.) and you just use Age within your domain? It might be similar to name not being greater than 50 characters. Our domain usually doesn't care how long a name is, but our storage mechanism may care.","date":"2022-11-27T21:50:06.305Z"},{"_id":"6d25e7e1-0ea3-4cfc-8a73-aad49f517a68","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"7d5a50b0-485e-11ed-b8aa-b9c9b5e9b3ca","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"That's the way I've always done it. If that's too burdensome, they could write their own serializers. I would say that such serializers belong to the application, though, since the app is the one with the requirement that the value object be read/written as JSON or whatever.","date":"2022-12-30T03:05:57.5014002Z"},{"_id":"bc815d75-7f07-4349-8500-b8128bd98577","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"74709710-6e9d-11ed-92eb-7ff19b5e5bb3","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"So far, I've just done my validation at the boundaries. It depends on how defensive you want to get; you *can* define your own property setters to ensure validation is still complete, but then you can also have situations where you need to set multiple properties before the object can be considered valid, and I'm not wild about temporarily turning off validation and then turning it back on. There isn't a great solution that handles everything ATM.\n\nGood point about the domain vs technical limitation. It would be great if our domains could ignore technical limitations, but it's usually more painful to have that kind of exception happen at the storage layer instead of as close as possible to the user. So, I usually do propagate technical limitations up.","date":"2022-12-30T02:51:42.1239699Z"},{"_id":"142dda4a-6117-4833-8b64-15ff7ac1f67c","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"754672131bf84b01ef8294606d8e4190","authorName":"Steve Dunn","authorUri":"https://dunnhq.com","message":"Thanks for the article. You might find Vogen interesting. It's a source generator for wrapping primitives:\n\nhttps://github.com/stevedunn/vogen\n","date":"2023-03-01T14:21:07.8767434Z"},{"_id":"4db09c1c-56ba-4b35-aa31-99ddeb7f59b4","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","authorName":"Nick","authorUri":"","message":"Happened across this post while looking for something else and had a question about your use of value records as IDs.\n\nI've taken this same approach in the past and do like how much easier value records are to make \"do the right thing\".  However, one thing I've gone back and forth on is what to do with empty or missing values. I'm curious what your thoughts are on the best approach when an object may or may not have a `CustomerId`, for example.  Would you make it nullable, compare it with `default`, or reference some sort of `CustomerId.Empty` value?  Or maybe something else?\n\nEach options has downsides, but I admit I like avoiding the repeated and easily missed null checks.  This does mean that `default` needs to have a valid meaning, which might not be the case for all primitives, such as a wrapped `int`.  And the third way requires more code to support the empty value, somewhat undermining the simplicity.\n\n(Aside: The value I've gotten from reading your articles and posts over the years has been immense.  Thank you!)","date":"2024-08-05T23:01:57.1897593Z"},{"_id":"678ce33f-9e2f-476e-8049-f31dd918a68a","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"4db09c1c-56ba-4b35-aa31-99ddeb7f59b4","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"I've done it both ways. As you've noted, there are disadvantages to both approaches. I don't like `null` *and* I don't like magic values. I guess I'm just an old grumpy developer...\n\nI would say I tend to use `null` in most cases, but it's certainly not a hill I'm going to die on. The whole `null` vs sentinel value is a wider design topic that I don't feel I have an authoritative answer on.","date":"2024-08-15T08:19:37.8231469Z"},{"_id":"637b7563-56a6-4805-b289-98806cf02b35","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"a9c8299378e038c01938b70c9836442b","authorName":"ungerfall","authorUri":"","message":"Thanks for the article. In Azure AI Search the facetable fields cannot be `null`. Do you it is a good usage to introduce `record struct FacetableString` primitive that has implicit convertions from `string?` and back to `string` ensuring no null values","date":"2025-03-12T23:13:16.6022354Z"},{"_id":"3b25561c-b1ea-42a8-9231-3410365e7aff","postId":"2022_10_modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records-b4619e8d-ff25-3436-9580-1327163e2a81","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/10/modern-csharp-techniques-2-value-records.html","replyTo":"637b7563-56a6-4805-b289-98806cf02b35","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"I'm not sure if I have a good idea of what you're proposing. In general, I avoid implicit conversions entirely, and do the conversions to and from my value records explicitly.","date":"2025-07-18T20:25:23.4420032Z"}]